DATE.d: Returns the serial number of a particular date

DATEDIF.d: Calculates the number of days, months, or years between two dates

DATEVALUE.d: Converts a date in the form of text to a serial number

DAY.d: Returns the day of the month, a number from 1 to 31

DAYS.d: Returns the number of days between two dates

DAYS360.d: Returns the number of days between two dates based on a 360-day year

EDATE.d: Returns the serial number of the date that is the indicated number of months before or after the start date

EOMONTH.d: Returns the serial number of the last day of the month before or after a specified number of months

HOUR.d: Returns the hour of a time value

ISOWEEKNUM.d: Returns the ISO week number of the year for a given date

MINUTE.d: Returns the minute of a time value

MONTH.d: Returns the month of a date value, an integer from 1 to 12

NETWORKDAYS.d: Returns the number of whole workdays between two dates

NETWORKDAYS.INTL.d: Returns the number of whole workdays between two dates using parameters to indicate which and how many days are weekend days

NOW.d: Returns the serial number of the current date and time

SECOND.d: Returns the seconds of a time value

TIME.d: Returns the serial number of a particular time

TIMEVALUE.d: Converts a time in the form of text to a serial number

TODAY.d: Returns the serial number of today's date

WEEKDAY.d: Returns the day of the week corresponding to a date

WEEKNUM.d: Returns the week number in the year

WORKDAY.d: Returns the serial number of the date before or after a specified number of workdays

WORKDAY.INTL.d: Returns the serial number of the date before or after a specified number of workdays using parameters to indicate which and how many days are weekend days

YEAR.d: Returns the year of a date value

YEARFRAC.d: Returns the year fraction representing the number of whole days between start_date and end_date

BESSELI.d: Returns the modified Bessel function In(x)

BESSELK.d: Returns the modified Bessel function Kn(x)

BIN2DEC.d: Converts a binary number to decimal

BIN2HEX.d: Converts a binary number to hexadecimal

BIN2OCT.d: Converts a binary number to octal

BITAND.d: Returns a bitwise 'AND' of two numbers

BITLSHIFT.d: Returns a number shifted left by shift_amount bits

BITRSHIFT.d: Returns a number shifted right by shift_amount bits

BITXOR.d: Returns the bitwise 'exclusive or' value of two numbers

COMPLEX.d: Converts real and imaginary coefficients into a complex number

CONVERT.d: Converts a number from one measurement system to another

DEC2BIN.d: Converts a decimal number to binary

DEC2HEX.d: Converts a decimal number to hexadecimal

DEC2OCT.d: Converts a decimal number to octal

DELTA.d: Tests whether two numbers are equal

GESTEP.d: Tests whether a number is greater than a threshold value

HEX2BIN.d: Converts a hexadecimal number to binary

HEX2DEC.d: Converts a hexadecimal number to decimal

HEX2OCT.d: Converts a hexadecimal number to octal

IMABS.d: Returns the absolute value (modulus) of a complex number

IMAGINARY.d: Returns the imaginary coefficient of a complex number

IMARGUMENT.d: Returns the argument theta, an angle expressed in radians

IMCONJUGATE.d: Returns the complex conjugate of a complex number

IMCOS.d: Returns the cosine of a complex number

IMCOSH.d: Returns the hyperbolic cosine of a complex number

IMCOT.d: Returns the cotangent of a complex number

IMCSC.d: Returns the cosecant of a complex number

IMCSCH.d: Returns the hyperbolic cosecant of a complex number

IMDIV.d: Returns the quotient of two complex numbers

IMEXP.d: Returns the exponential of a complex number

IMLN.d: Returns the natural logarithm of a complex number

IMLOG10.d: Returns the base-10 logarithm of a complex number

IMLOG2.d: Returns the base-2 logarithm of a complex number

IMPOWER.d: Returns a complex number raised to an integer power

IMPRODUCT.d: Returns the product of 1 to 255 complex numbers

IMREAL.d: Returns the real coefficient of a complex number

IMSEC.d: Returns the secant of a complex number

IMSECH.d: Returns the hyperbolic secant of a complex number

IMSIN.d: Returns the sine of a complex number

IMSINH.d: Returns the hyperbolicsinevalue of complex number

IMSQRT.d: Returns the square root of a complex number

IMSUB.d: Returns the difference between two complex numbers

IMSUM.d: Returns the sum of complex numbers

IMTAN.d: Returns the tangent of a complex number

OCT2BIN.d: Converts an octal number to binary

OCT2DEC.d: Converts an octal number to decimal

OCT2HEX.d: Converts an octal number to hexadecimal

DAVERAGE.d: Calculates the average of numeric values in a column of a list or database that meet given conditions

DCOUNT.d: Counts the number of numeric cells in a field (column) of database records that meet given conditions

DCOUNTA.d: Counts the number of non-empty cells in a field (column) of database records that meet specified conditions

DGET.d: Extracts a unique record from a database that meets specified conditions

DMAX.d: Returns the maximum value in a field (column) of database records that meet given conditions

DMIN.d: Returns the minimum value in a field (column) of database records that meet given conditions

DPRODUCT.d: Multiplies the values in a field (column) of database records that meet specified conditions

DSTDEV.d: Estimates the standard deviation of data based on a sample from selected database entries

DSTDEVP.d: Calculates the standard deviation of data using the selected database items as the entire population

DSUM.d: Returns the sum of values in a field (column) of database records that meet given conditions

DVAR.d: Estimates the variance of data based on a sample from selected database entries

DVARP.d: Calculates the population variance of data using the selected database items as the entire population

CHAR.d: Returns the character specified by a code number from the character set used by your computer

CLEAN.d: Removes all non-printable characters from text

CODE.d: Returns the numeric code for the first character in a text string, based on the character set used by your computer

CONCATENATE.d: Joins several text strings into one text string

CONCAT.d: Joins a list or text string range

DOLLAR.d: Converts a number to text using currency format

EXACT.d: Compares two strings to determine if they are exactly the same (case-sensitive). Returns TRUE or FALSE

FIND.d: Finds one text value within another (case-sensitive)

FINDB.d: Finds one text string within another text string and returns the number of the starting position of the first text string from the first character of the second text string. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

FIXED.d: Rounds a number to the specified number of decimals, formats the number in decimal format using a period and commas, and returns the result as text

LEFT.d: Returns the leftmost characters from a text value

LEFTB.d: Returns the first character or characters in a text string, based on the number of bytes you specify. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

LEN.d: Returns the number of characters in a text string

LENB.d: Returns the number of bytes used to represent the characters in a text string. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

MID.d: Returns a specific number of characters from a text string starting at the position you specify

MIDB.d: Returns a specific number of characters from a text string, starting at the position you specify, based on the number of bytes you specify. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

NUMBERVALUE.d: Converts text to a number in a locale-independent way

PROPER.d: Capitalizes the first letter in each word of a text string and converts all other letters to lowercase

REPLACE.d: Replaces part of a text string with a different text string

REPLACEB.d: Replaces part of a text string with a different text string, based on the number of bytes you specify. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

REPT.d: Repeats text a given number of times. Use REPT to fill a cell with a number of instances of a text string

RIGHT.d: Returns the rightmost characters from a text value

RIGHTB.d: Returns the last character or characters in a text string, based on the number of bytes you specify. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

SEARCH.d: Finds one text value within another (not case-sensitive)

SEARCHB.d: Finds one text string within another text string and returns the number of the starting position of the first text string from the first character of the second text string. This function is for use with languages that use the double-byte character set (DBCS). Languages that support DBCS include Japanese, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), and Korean.

SUBSTITUTE.d: Substitutes new text for old text in a text string

T.d: Checks whether a value is text, and returns the text if it is, or returns double quotes (empty text) if it is not

TEXT.d: Converts a numeric value to text using the specified number format

TEXTJOIN.d: Joins a list or text string range using a delimiter

UNICHAR.d: Returns the Unicode character referenced by the given numeric value

UNICODE.d: Returns the number (code point) for the first character of the text

VALUE.d: Converts a text string that represents a number to a number

AVEDEV.d: Returns the average of the absolute deviations of data points from their mean. Arguments can be numbers, names, arrays, or references that contain numbers

AVERAGE.d: Returns the average (arithmetic mean) of its arguments

AVERAGEA.d: Returns the average (arithmetic mean) of all arguments. Text and FALSE evaluate as 0; TRUE evaluates as 1. Arguments can be numbers, names, arrays, or references

AVERAGEIF.d: Finds the average (arithmetic mean) of cells specified by a given condition

AVERAGEIFS.d: Finds the average (arithmetic mean) of cells specified by a group of given conditions

BETADIST.d: Returns the cumulative beta probability density function

BETAINV.d: Returns the inverse of the cumulative beta probability density function (BETADIST)

BETA.DIST.d: Returns the beta probability distribution function

BETA.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the cumulative beta distribution for a given probability

BINOMDIST.d: Returns the individual term binomial distribution probability

BINOM.DIST.d: Returns the individual term binomial distribution probability

BINOM.DIST.RANGE.d: Returns the probability of a trial result using a binomial distribution

BINOM.INV.d: Returns the smallest value for which the cumulative binomial distribution is greater than or equal to a criterion value

CHIDIST.d: Returns the right-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution

CHIINV.d: Returns the inverse of the right-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution for a given probability

CHITEST.d: Returns the test for independence: the value from the chi-squared distribution for the statistic and the appropriate degrees of freedom

CHISQ.DIST.d: Returns the left-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution

CHISQ.DIST.RT.d: Returns the right-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution

CHISQ.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the left-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution for a given probability

CHISQ.INV.RT.d: Returns the inverse of the right-tailed probability of the chi-squared distribution for a given probability

CHISQ.TEST.d: Returns the test for independence: the value from the chi-squared distribution for the statistic and the appropriate degrees of freedom

CONFIDENCE.d: Returns the confidence interval for a population mean using a normal distribution

CONFIDENCE.NORM.d: Returns the confidence interval for a population mean using a normal distribution

CONFIDENCE.T.d: Returns the confidence interval for a population mean using a Student's t distribution

CORREL.d: Returns the correlation coefficient between two groups of numeric values

COUNT.d: Counts how many numbers are in the list of arguments

COUNTA.d: Counts the number of non-empty cells in a range

COUNTBLANK.d: Counts the number of empty cells in a range

COUNTIF.d: Counts the number of cells in a range that meet given conditions

COUNTIFS.d: Counts the number of cells specified by a group of given conditions

COVAR.d: Returns covariance, the average of the products of deviations for each data point pair

COVARIANCE.P.d: Returns population covariance, the average of the products of deviations for each data point pair in two groups of numeric values

COVARIANCE.S.d: Returns sample covariance, the average of the products of deviations for each data point pair in two groups of numeric values

CRITBINOM.d: Returns the smallest value for which the cumulative binomial distribution is greater than or equal to a criterion value

DEVSQ.d: Returns the sum of squares of deviations of data points from their sample mean

FDIST.d: Returns the (right-tailed) F probability distribution (degree of diversity) for two groups of data

FINV.d: Returns the inverse of the (right-tailed) F probability distribution. If p = FDIST(x,...), then FINV(p,...) = x

FTEST.d: Returns the result of an F-test: the two-tailed probability that the variances in Array1 and Array2 are not significantly different

F.DIST.d: Returns the (left-tailed) F probability distribution for two groups of data

F.DIST.RT.d: Returns the (right-tailed) F probability distribution for two groups of data

F.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the (left-tailed) F probability distribution. If p = F.DIST(x,...), then F.INV(p,...) = x

F.INV.RT.d: Returns the inverse of the (right-tailed) F probability distribution. If p = F.DIST.RT(x,...), then F.INV.RT(p,...) = x

F.TEST.d: Returns the result of an F-test: the two-tailed probability that the variances in Array1 and Array2 are not significantly different

FISHERINV.d: Returns the inverse of the Fisher transformation. If y = FISHER(x), then FISHERINV(y) = x

FORECAST.d: Calculates or predicts a future value based on existing values using a linear trend

FORECAST.ETS.d: Returns a forecasted value for a specific future target date using exponential smoothing

FORECAST.ETS.CONFINT.d: Returns a confidence interval for the forecasted value at the specified target date

FORECAST.ETS.SEASONALITY.d: Returns the length of the repetitive pattern detected for the specified time series

FORECAST.ETS.STAT.d: Returns the requested statistical information for the forecast

FORECAST.LINEAR.d: Calculates or predicts a future value based on existing values using a linear trend

FREQUENCY.d: Returns a vertical array of the frequency distribution of a group of data

GAMMAINV.d: Returns the inverse of the cumulative gamma distribution for a given probability. If p = GAMMADIST(x,...), then GAMMAINV(p,...) = x

GAMMA.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the cumulative gamma distribution for a given probability

GAMMALN.d: Returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function

GAMMALN.PRECISE.d: Returns the natural logarithm of the gamma function

GAUSS.d: Returns 0.5 less than the standard normal cumulative distribution

GEOMEAN.d: Returns the geometric mean of a positive array or numeric value range

GROWTH.d: Returns an array of y-values for an exponential regression fit curve

HARMEAN.d: Returns the harmonic mean of a group of positive numbers: the reciprocal of the arithmetic mean of reciprocals

INTERCEPT.d: Calculates the point at which a line will intersect the y-axis by using existing x-values and y-values

KURT.d: Returns the kurtosis of a group of data

LARGE.d: Returns the k-th largest value in a data group. For example, the fifth largest value

LINEST.d: Returns the parameters of a linear regression formula

LOGEST.d: Returns the parameters of an exponential regression fit curve formula

LOGINV.d: Returns the inverse of the lognormal cumulative distribution function of x, where ln(x) is normally distributed with parameters mean and standard_dev

LOGNORM.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the lognormal distribution function for a given probability

LOGNORMDIST.d: Returns the cumulative lognormal distribution of x, where ln(x) is normally distributed with parameters mean and standard_dev

MAX.d: Returns the maximum value in a list of arguments

MAXA.d: Returns the maximum value in a group of parameters (does not ignore logical values and text)

MAXIFS.d: Returns the maximum value of cells specified by a group of given conditions

MEDIAN.d: Returns the median of a group of numbers

MIN.d: Returns the minimum value in a list of arguments

MINA.d: Returns the minimum value in a group of parameters (does not ignore logical values and text)

MINIFS.d: Returns the minimum value of cells specified by a group of given conditions

MODE.d: Returns the mode (most frequently occurring number) of a group of data or data range

MODE.MULT.d: Returns a vertical array of the most frequently occurring or repeated numeric values in a group of data or data range. Use =TRANSPOSE(MODE.MULT(number1,number2,...)) for a horizontal array

MODE.SNGL.d: Returns the most frequently occurring or repeated numeric value in a group of data or data range

NEGBINOM.DIST.d: Returns the negative binomial distribution function value

NEGBINOMDIST.d: Returns the negative binomial distribution function: the probability that there will be Number_f failures before the Number_s-th success, with Probability_s probability of success

NORM.DIST.d: Returns the normal distribution function value

NORMDIST.d: Returns the cumulative normal distribution function value for a specified mean and standard deviation

NORM.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the normal distribution for a given probability

NORMINV.d: Returns the inverse of the cumulative normal distribution function for a specified mean and standard deviation

NORM.S.DIST.d: Returns the standard normal distribution function value

NORMSDIST.d: Returns the standard normal cumulative distribution function value (with zero mean and one standard deviation)

NORM.S.INV.d: Returns the inverse of the standard normal distribution

NORMSINV.d: Returns the inverse of the standard normal cumulative distribution (with zero mean and one standard deviation)

PEARSON.d: Returns the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient r

PERCENTILE.d: Returns the k-th percentile value of an array

PERCENTILE.EXC.d: Returns the k-th percentile value of an array, where k is between 0 and 1, exclusive

PERCENTILE.INC.d: Returns the k-th percentile value of an array, where k is between 0 and 1, inclusive

PERCENTRANK.d: Returns the percentage rank of a specific numeric value in a group of numbers

PERCENTRANK.EXC.d: Returns the percentage rank of a specific numeric value in a group of numbers (between 0 and 1, exclusive)

PERCENTRANK.INC.d: Returns the percentage rank of a specific numeric value in a group of numbers (between 0 and 1, inclusive)

PERMUT.d: Returns the number of permutations for a given number of objects that can be selected from a set

PERMUTATIONA.d: Returns the number of permutations for a given number of objects (with repetitions allowed) that can be selected from the total number of objects

PHI.d: Returns the density function value of the standard normal distribution

PROB.d: Returns the sum of probabilities corresponding to the event set that meets specified conditions in a probability event group

QUARTILE.d: Returns the quartile point of a group of data

QUARTILE.INC.d: Returns the quartile point of a group of data based on percentile values from 0 to 1 (inclusive)

QUARTILE.EXC.d: Returns the quartile point of a group of data based on percentile values from 0 to 1 (exclusive)

RANK.d: Returns the size rank of a number in a column of numbers relative to other numeric values

RANK.AVG.d: Returns the size rank of a number in a column of numbers relative to other numeric values. If multiple numeric values have the same rank, returns the average of the ranks

RANK.EQ.d: Returns the size rank of a number in a column of numbers relative to other numeric values. If multiple numeric values have the same rank, returns the best rank for that group of numeric values

RSQ.d: Returns the square of the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient for given data points

SKEW.d: Returns the skewness of a distribution: used to characterize the degree of asymmetry of a distribution around its mean

SKEW.P.d: Returns the skewness of a distribution based on a population: used to characterize the degree of asymmetry of a distribution around its mean

SLOPE.d: Returns the slope of the linear regression line formula that passes through given data points

SMALL.d: Returns the k-th smallest value in a data group

STANDARDIZE.d: Returns a normalized value from a distribution characterized by mean and standard_dev

STDEV.d: Estimates standard deviation based on a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the sample)

STDEV.P.d: Calculates standard deviation based on the entire population of a given sample (ignores logical values and text)

STDEV.S.d: Estimates standard deviation based on a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the sample)

STDEVA.d: Estimates standard deviation based on a given sample (including logical values and text). Text and logical value FALSE evaluate as 0; logical value TRUE evaluates as 1

STDEVP.d: Calculates standard deviation based on the entire population of a given sample (ignores logical values and text)

STDEVPA.d: Calculates standard deviation for the entire population of a sample (including logical values and text). Text and logical value FALSE evaluate as 0; logical value TRUE evaluates as 1

STEYX.d: Returns the standard error of the predicted y-value for each x in the regression using linear regression

TINV.d: Returns the two-tailed interval point of the Student's t-distribution

T.INV.d: Returns the left-tailed interval point of the Student's t-distribution

T.INV.2T.d: Returns the two-tailed interval point of the Student's t-distribution

T.TEST.d: Returns the probability value of the Student's t-test

TREND.d: Returns an array of y-values for a linear regression fit line

TRIMMEAN.d: Returns the trimmed average of a group of data

TTEST.d: Returns the probability value of the Student's t-test

VAR.d: Estimates variance based on a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the sample)

VAR.P.d: Calculates variance based on the entire population of a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the sample)

VAR.S.d: Estimates variance based on a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the sample)

VARA.d: Estimates variance based on a given sample (including logical values and text). Text and logical value FALSE evaluate as 0; logical value TRUE evaluates as 1

VARP.d: Calculates variance based on the entire population of a given sample (ignores logical values and text in the entire population)

VARPA.d: Calculates variance for the entire population of a sample (including logical values and text). Text and logical value FALSE evaluate as 0; logical value TRUE evaluates as 1

Z.TEST.d: Returns the one-tailed P-value of a z-test

ZTEST.d: Returns the one-tailed P-value of a z-test

ACCRINT.d: Returns the accrued interest for a security that pays periodic interest

ACCRINTM.d: Returns the accrued interest for a security that pays interest at maturity

AMORDEGRC.d: Returns the linear depreciation of an asset for each accounting period

AMORLINC.d: Returns the linear depreciation of an asset for each accounting period

COUPDAYBS.d: Returns the number of days from the beginning of the coupon period to the settlement date

COUPDAYS.d: Returns the number of days in the coupon period that contains the settlement date

COUPDAYSNC.d: Returns the number of days from the settlement date to the next coupon payment date

COUPNCD.d: Returns the next coupon date after the settlement date

COUPNUM.d: Returns the number of coupons payable between the settlement date and maturity date

COUPPCD.d: Returns the previous coupon date before the settlement date

CUMIPMT.d: Returns the cumulative interest paid on a loan between two payment periods

CUMPRINC.d: Returns the cumulative principal paid on a loan between two payment periods

DB.d: Returns the depreciation value of an asset for a specified period using the fixed-declining balance method

DDB.d: Returns the depreciation value of an asset for a specified period using the double-declining balance method or another specified method

DISC.d: Returns the discount rate for a security

DOLLARDE.d: Converts a dollar price expressed as a fraction into a dollar price expressed as a decimal number

DOLLARFR.d: Converts a dollar price expressed as a decimal number into a dollar price expressed as a fraction

DURATION.d: Returns the annual duration of a security that pays periodic interest

EFFECT.d: Returns the effective annual interest rate

FV.d: Returns the future value of an investment based on periodic, constant payments and a constant interest rate

FVSCHEDULE.d: Returns the future value of an initial principal after applying a series of compound interest rates

INTRATE.d: Returns the interest rate for a fully invested security

IPMT.d: Returns the interest portion of a payment for a given period for an investment or loan with periodic payments and a constant interest rate

IRR.d: Returns the internal rate of return for a series of cash flows

ISPMT.d: Returns the interest payment for a simple (non-compounded) loan

MDURATION.d: Returns the modified Macaulay duration for a security with an assumed par value of $100

MIRR.d: Returns the internal rate of return for a series of periodic cash flows, considering both the cost of the investment and the interest received on reinvestment of cash

NOMINAL.d: Returns the annual nominal interest rate

NPER.d: Returns the number of periods for an investment or loan based on periodic, constant payments and a constant interest rate

NPV.d: Returns the net present value of an investment based on a series of periodic cash flows and a discount rate

ODDFPRICE.a: (settlement; maturity; issue; first_coupon; rate; yld; redemption; frequency; [basis])
ODDFPRICE.d: Returns the price per $100 face value of a security with an odd first period

ODDFYIELD.a: (settlement; maturity; issue; first_coupon; rate; pr; redemption; frequency; [basis])
ODDFYIELD.d: Returns the yield of a security with an odd first period

ODDLPRICE.a: (settlement; maturity; last_interest; rate; yld; redemption; frequency; [basis])
ODDLPRICE.d: Returns the price per $100 face value of a security with an odd last period

ODDLYIELD.a: (settlement; maturity; last_interest; rate; pr; redemption; frequency; [basis])
ODDLYIELD.d: Returns the yield of a security with an odd last period

PDURATION.d: Returns the number of periods required for an investment to reach a specified value

PMT.d: Calculates the payment for a loan based on constant payments and a constant interest rate

PPMT.d: Returns the principal portion of a payment for a given period for an investment or loan with periodic payments and a constant interest rate

PRICE.d: Returns the price per $100 face value of a security that pays periodic interest

PRICEDISC.d: Returns the price per $100 face value of a discounted security

PRICEMAT.d: Returns the price per $100 face value of a security that pays interest at maturity

PV.d: Returns the present value of an investment: the total value now of a series of future payments (or the present value of a lump-sum payment)

RATE.d: Returns the interest rate per period of an investment or loan. For example, use 6%/4 for quarterly payments at an annual interest rate of 6%

RECEIVED.d: Returns the amount received at maturity for a fully invested security

RRI.d: Returns an equivalent interest rate for the growth of an investment

SLN.d: Returns the straight-line depreciation of an asset for one period

SYD.d: Returns the sum-of-years' digits depreciation of an asset for a specified period

TBILLEQ.d: Returns the bond-equivalent yield for a Treasury bill

TBILLPRICE.d: Returns the price per $100 face value for a Treasury bill

TBILLYIELD.d: Returns the yield for a Treasury bill

VDB.d: Returns the depreciation of an asset for a specified or partial period using a declining balance method or another specified method

XIRR.d: Returns the internal rate of return for a schedule of cash flows

XNPV.d: Returns the net present value for a schedule of cash flows

YIELD.d: Returns the yield on a security that pays periodic interest

YIELDDISC.d: Returns the annual yield for a discounted security, such as a Treasury bill

YIELDMAT.d: Returns the annual yield of a security that pays interest at maturity

ABS.d: Returns the absolute value of a number, a number without its sign

ACOS.d: Returns the arccosine of a number in radians, in the range 0 to Pi. The arccosine is the angle whose cosine is Number

ACOSH.d: Returns the inverse hyperbolic cosine value

ACOT.d: Returns the arccotangent of a number in radians, in the range 0 to Pi

ACOTH.d: Returns the inverse hyperbolic cotangent of a number

AGGREGATE.d: Returns an aggregate in a list or database

ARABIC.d: Converts a Roman numeral to an Arabic number

ASC.d: For double-byte character set (DBCS) languages, this function converts full-width (double-byte) characters to half-width (single-byte) characters

ASIN.d: Returns the arcsine of a number in radians, in the range -Pi/2 to Pi/2

ASINH.d: Returns the inverse hyperbolic sine value

ATAN.d: Returns the arctangent value in radians, in the range -Pi/2 to Pi/2

ATAN2.d: Returns the arctangent from x- and y-coordinates. Returns a value in the range -Pi to Pi (excluding -Pi)

ATANH.d: Returns the inverse hyperbolic tangent value

BASE.d: Converts a number into a text representation with the given radix (base)

CEILING.d: Rounds a number up to the nearest multiple of the specified significance

CEILING.MATH.d: Rounds a number up to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of the specified significance

CEILING.PRECISE.d: Returns a number rounded up to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of significance

COMBIN.d: Returns the number of combinations for a given number of items from a set

COMBINA.d: Returns the number of combinations for a given number of items (with repetitions allowed)

COS.d: Returns the cosine of the given angle

COT.d: Returns the cotangent of an angle

COTH.d: Returns the hyperbolic cotangent of a number

CSC.d: Returns the cosecant of an angle

CSCH.d: Returns the hyperbolic cosecant of an angle

DECIMAL.d: Converts a text representation of a number in a given base into a decimal number

ECMA.CEILING.d: Rounds a number up to the nearest multiple of the specified significance

EVEN.d: Rounds positive numbers up to the nearest even integer, and negative numbers down to the nearest even integer

EXP.d: Returns e raised to the power of n

FACT.d: Returns the factorial of a number, equal to 1*2*...*Number

FACTDOUBLE.d: Returns the double factorial of a number

FLOOR.d: Rounds a number down to the nearest multiple of the specified significance

FLOOR.PRECISE.d: Returns a number rounded down to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of significance

FLOOR.MATH.d: Rounds a number down to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of the specified significance

INT.d: Rounds a number down to the nearest integer

ISO.CEILING.d: Returns a number rounded up to the nearest integer or to the nearest multiple of significance. Regardless of the sign of the number, the number is rounded up. However, if the number or significance is 0, then 0 is returned

LN.d: Returns the natural logarithm of a given number

LOG.d: Returns the logarithm of a number to the specified base

LOG10.d: Returns the base-10 logarithm of a given number

MDETERM.d: Returns the matrix determinant of an array

MINVERSE.d: Returns the matrix inverse of an array

MMULT.d: Returns the matrix product of two arrays. The result matrix has the same number of rows as array1 and the same number of columns as array2

MOD.d: Returns the remainder after division of two numbers

MROUND.d: Returns a number rounded to the desired multiple

MULTINOMIAL.d: Returns the multinomial of a group of numbers

MUNIT.d: Returns the unit matrix for the specified dimension

ODD.d: Rounds positive (negative) numbers up (down) to the nearest odd integer

PI.d: Returns the value of Pi, 3.14159265358979, accurate to 15 digits

POWER.d: Returns the result of a number raised to a power

QUOTIENT.d: Returns the integer portion of a division

RAND.d: Returns a random number greater than or equal to 0 and less than 1, evenly distributed (changes on recalculation)

RANDARRAY.d: Returns an array of random numbers

RANDBETWEEN.d: Returns a random number between the numbers you specify

ROMAN.d: Converts an Arabic number to text, as a Roman numeral

ROUND.d: Rounds a number to a specified number of digits

SEC.d: Returns the secant of an angle

SECH.d: Returns the hyperbolic secant of an angle

SERIESSUM.d: Returns the sum of a power series based on a formula

SIGN.d: Returns the sign of a number: returns 1 if positive, 0 if zero, -1 if negative

SIN.d: Returns the sine of the given angle

SQRT.d: Returns the square root of a number

SQRTPI.d: Returns the square root of (number * Pi)

SUBTOTAL.d: Returns a subtotal in a data list or database

SUM.d: Adds all the numbers in a range of cells

SUMIF.d: Sums the cells that meet a condition

SUMIFS.d: Sums the cells specified by a group of given conditions

SUMPRODUCT.d: Returns the sum of the products of corresponding arrays or ranges

SUMSQ.d: Returns the sum of the squares of all arguments. Arguments can be numbers, arrays, names, or references to cells containing numbers

SUMX2MY2.d: Calculates the sum of the squares of the differences of corresponding numeric values in two arrays

SUMX2PY2.d: Calculates the sum of the squares of corresponding numeric values in two arrays

SUMXMY2.d: Returns the sum of the squares of the differences of corresponding numeric values in two arrays

TAN.d: Returns the tangent of the given angle

TRUNC.d: Truncates a number to an integer or to a specified number of decimal places

ADDRESS.d: Creates a text reference to a cell in a workbook

CHOOSE.d: Chooses a value or action from a list of values, based on an index number

COLUMN.d: Returns the column number of a reference

COLUMNS.d: Returns the number of columns in a reference or array

FORMULATEXT.d: Returns a formula as a string

HLOOKUP.d: Looks for a value in the top row of a table or array of values and returns the value in the same column from a row you specify

HYPERLINK.d: Creates a shortcut or link that opens a document stored on a hard drive, network server, or the Internet

INDEX.d: Returns a value or reference of the cell at the intersection of a particular row and column, in a given range

INDIRECT.d: Returns the reference specified by a text string

LOOKUP.d: Looks up a value from a one-row or one-column range or from an array. Provided for backward compatibility

MATCH.d: Returns the relative position of an item in an array that matches a specified value in a specified order

OFFSET.d: Returns a reference offset from a given reference by a specified number of rows and columns

ROW.d: Returns the row number of a reference

ROWS.d: Returns the number of rows in a reference or array

UNIQUE.d: Returns unique values from a range or array

VLOOKUP.d: Looks for a value in the leftmost column of a table, and then returns a value in the same row from a column you specify

XLOOKUP.d: Searches for a match in a range or array and returns the corresponding item from a second range or array. By default, uses an exact match

CELL.d: Returns information about the formatting, location, or contents of a cell

ERROR.TYPE.d: Returns a number corresponding to an error value

ISBLANK.d: Checks whether a reference is to an empty cell, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISERR.d: Checks whether a value is an error other than #N/A, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISERROR.d: Checks whether a value is an error, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISEVEN.d: Returns TRUE if number is even

ISFORMULA.d: Checks whether a reference refers to a cell containing a formula, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISLOGICAL.d: Checks whether a value is a logical value (TRUE or FALSE), and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISNA.d: Checks whether a value is #N/A, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISNONTEXT.d: Checks whether a value is not text (empty cells are not text), and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISNUMBER.d: Checks whether a value is a number, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISODD.d: Returns TRUE if number is odd

ISREF.d: Checks whether a value is a reference, and returns TRUE or FALSE

ISTEXT.d: Checks whether a value is text, and returns TRUE or FALSE

N.d: Converts a value to a number. Dates convert to serial numbers, TRUE converts to 1, other values convert to 0

NA.d: Returns the error value #N/A (value not available)

SHEET.d: Returns the sheet number of the referenced worksheet

SHEETS.d: Returns the number of sheets in a reference

TYPE.d: Returns the data type of a value as an integer: number = 1; text = 2; logical value = 4; error value = 16; array = 64; compound data = 128

AND.d: Checks whether all arguments are TRUE, and returns TRUE if all arguments are TRUE

IF.d: Returns one value if a condition you specify evaluates to TRUE and another value if it evaluates to FALSE

IFS.d: Checks whether one or more conditions are met and returns a value corresponding to the first TRUE condition

IFERROR.d: If an expression is an error, returns value_if_error, otherwise returns the value of the expression

IFNA.d: If an expression resolves to #N/A, returns the value you specify, otherwise returns the result of the expression

NOT.d: Reverses the logic of its argument: returns FALSE when argument is TRUE, returns TRUE when argument is FALSE

OR.d: Returns TRUE if any argument is TRUE; returns FALSE only if all arguments are FALSE

SWITCH.d: Evaluates an expression against a list of values and returns the result corresponding to the first matching value. If there is no match, returns an optional default value

XOR.d: Returns the logical exclusive OR of all arguments

TEXTBEFORE.d: Returns text that occurs before a delimiter character

TEXTAFTER.d: Returns text that occurs after a delimiter character

TEXTSPLIT.d: Splits text into rows or columns using delimiters

WRAPROWS.d: Wraps a row or column vector into a row after a specified number of values

VSTACK.d: Vertically stacks arrays into a single array

HSTACK.d: Horizontally stacks arrays into a single array

CHOOSEROWS.d: Returns rows from an array or reference

CHOOSECOLS.d: Returns columns from an array or reference

TOCOL.d: Returns an array in a single column

TOROW.d: Returns an array in a single row

WRAPCOLS.d: Wraps a row or column vector into a column after a specified number of values

TAKE.d: Returns rows or columns from the start or end of an array

DROP.d: Removes rows or columns from the start or end of an array

EXPAND.d: Expands an array to specified dimensions

XMATCH.d: Returns the relative position of an item in an array. By default, requires an exact match

ARRAYTOTEXT.d: Returns the text representation of an array

SORTBY.d: Sorts a range or array based on the values in a corresponding range or array
